WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.325
Welcome to Anatomical terminology.

2
00:00:03.325 --> 00:00:07.683
A twenty-two-year-old medical student walks into the emergency department.

3
00:00:07.683 --> 00:00:10.284
They have pain in the front of their lower arm.

4
00:00:10.284 --> 00:00:13.728
The orthopaedic resident asks a series of quick questions.

5
00:00:13.728 --> 00:00:16.118
Is it on the anterior or posterior aspect?

6
00:00:16.118 --> 00:00:17.454
Is it medial or lateral?

7
00:00:17.454 --> 00:00:19.000
Is it proximal to the wrist,

8
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:20.265
or distal to the elbow?

9
00:00:20.265 --> 00:00:21.460
The student freezes.

10
00:00:21.460 --> 00:00:23.429
Not because the injury is serious,

11
00:00:23.429 --> 00:00:26.732
but because they do not yet share the resident's language.

12
00:00:26.732 --> 00:00:28.982
In one week, that language will be yours.

13
00:00:28.982 --> 00:00:31.231
Anatomical terminology is not jargon.

14
00:00:31.231 --> 00:00:32.145
It is precision.

15
00:00:32.145 --> 00:00:34.816
It removes ambiguity from clinical practice,

16
00:00:34.816 --> 00:00:36.643
from surgery, and from research.

17
00:00:36.643 --> 00:00:39.525
When a surgeon in one country describes a finding,

18
00:00:39.525 --> 00:00:43.602
a colleague anywhere in the world understands exactly what they mean.

19
00:00:43.602 --> 00:00:46.203
That shared language connects every doctor,

20
00:00:46.203 --> 00:00:49.507
every researcher, and every operating room on the planet.

21
00:00:49.507 --> 00:00:51.475
This week, you begin to build yours.

22
00:00:51.475 --> 00:00:57.426
Every directional term in anatomy is defined relative to one standard starting point:

23
00:00:57.426 --> 00:00:59.162
the anatomical position.

24
00:00:59.162 --> 00:01:02.468
In the anatomical position, the body is standing

25
00:01:02.468 --> 00:01:04.121
upright, facing forward.

26
00:01:04.121 --> 00:01:06.188
The feet are at shoulder width,

27
00:01:06.188 --> 00:01:08.089
with toes pointing forward.

28
00:01:08.089 --> 00:01:09.825
The arms hang at the sides,

29
00:01:09.825 --> 00:01:12.635
with the palms facing forward, not inward.

30
00:01:12.635 --> 00:01:15.859
That detail about the palms is easy to get wrong,

31
00:01:15.859 --> 00:01:17.760
so take a moment to lock it in.

32
00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:19.165
Why does this matter?

33
00:01:19.165 --> 00:01:25.364
Because the same body part can look very different depending on how a person is positioned.

34
00:01:25.364 --> 00:01:27.100
They might be lying in bed,

35
00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:30.985
sitting in a chair, or placed upside down inside a scanner.

36
00:01:30.985 --> 00:01:34.622
By always referring back to the anatomical position,

37
00:01:34.622 --> 00:01:38.672
every anatomist in the world works from the same reference,

38
00:01:38.672 --> 00:01:42.722
regardless of how the patient is actually lying or sitting.

39
00:01:42.722 --> 00:01:44.458
Think of it like a compass.

40
00:01:44.458 --> 00:01:46.855
No matter which direction you face,

41
00:01:46.855 --> 00:01:48.343
north is always north.

42
00:01:48.343 --> 00:01:51.318
The anatomical position is anatomy's north.

43
00:01:51.318 --> 00:01:55.038
Two resting positions you will encounter on the wards.

44
00:01:55.038 --> 00:01:56.939
Prone means lying face-down.

45
00:01:56.939 --> 00:01:58.757
Supine means lying face-up.

46
00:01:58.757 --> 00:02:02.064
A quick memory hook: prone is like a prone shooter,

47
00:02:02.064 --> 00:02:03.634
face toward the ground;

48
00:02:03.634 --> 00:02:06.775
supine is like sunbathing, face toward the sky.

49
00:02:06.775 --> 00:02:08.648
Imagine slicing a loaf of bread.

50
00:02:08.648 --> 00:02:10.449
Depending on which way you cut,

51
00:02:10.449 --> 00:02:13.403
you get a completely different view of the inside.

52
00:02:13.403 --> 00:02:15.133
Body planes work the same way.

53
00:02:15.133 --> 00:02:18.375
They are imaginary flat surfaces that divide the body,

54
00:02:18.375 --> 00:02:21.833
letting us describe location and orientation precisely.

55
00:02:21.833 --> 00:02:24.138
There are three primary planes to know.

56
00:02:24.138 --> 00:02:26.012
The first is the sagittal plane,

57
00:02:26.012 --> 00:02:29.110
which divides the body into right and left portions.

58
00:02:29.110 --> 00:02:31.343
When it runs exactly down the midline,

59
00:02:31.343 --> 00:02:33.433
it is called the midsagittal plane,

60
00:02:33.433 --> 00:02:35.234
also known as the median plane.

61
00:02:35.234 --> 00:02:37.179
When it sits slightly off-centre,

62
00:02:37.179 --> 00:02:39.124
it becomes a parasagittal plane.

63
00:02:39.124 --> 00:02:43.231
Think of slicing a burger straight down the middle from top to bottom.

64
00:02:43.231 --> 00:02:45.104
The second is the coronal plane,

65
00:02:45.104 --> 00:02:46.905
also called the frontal plane.

66
00:02:46.905 --> 00:02:49.643
It divides the body into the anterior portion,

67
00:02:49.643 --> 00:02:52.309
meaning the front, and the posterior portion,

68
00:02:52.309 --> 00:02:53.318
meaning the back.

69
00:02:53.318 --> 00:02:55.911
The name comes from the Latin word for crown.

70
00:02:55.911 --> 00:02:57.568
Picture a crown on your head,

71
00:02:57.568 --> 00:03:00.594
and the plane passing through it runs front to back.

72
00:03:00.594 --> 00:03:02.612
The third is the transverse plane,

73
00:03:02.612 --> 00:03:05.133
also called the axial or horizontal plane.

74
00:03:05.133 --> 00:03:07.871
It divides the body into the superior portion,

75
00:03:07.871 --> 00:03:10.753
meaning the upper part, and the inferior portion,

76
00:03:10.753 --> 00:03:12.122
meaning the lower part.

77
00:03:12.122 --> 00:03:16.157
Computed tomography scans produce images in the transverse plane.

78
00:03:16.157 --> 00:03:20.552
That is why the images look like horizontal slices of the body when viewed

79
00:03:20.552 --> 00:03:21.200
on a screen.

80
00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:26.386
Directional terms describe where one structure sits relative to another.

81
00:03:26.386 --> 00:03:30.066
All of them assume the body is in anatomical position,

82
00:03:30.066 --> 00:03:32.659
standing upright and facing forward.

83
00:03:32.659 --> 00:03:35.420
The first pair is superior and inferior.

84
00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:38.180
Superior means above, or toward the head.

85
00:03:38.180 --> 00:03:40.940
Inferior means below, or toward the feet.

86
00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:44.286
The heart, for example, is superior to the stomach.

87
00:03:44.286 --> 00:03:46.294
Next, anterior and posterior.

88
00:03:46.294 --> 00:03:49.305
Anterior means toward the front of the body,

89
00:03:49.305 --> 00:03:51.312
and it is also called ventral.

90
00:03:51.312 --> 00:03:53.571
Posterior means toward the back,

91
00:03:53.571 --> 00:03:55.494
and it is also called dorsal.

92
00:03:55.494 --> 00:03:58.004
The sternum is anterior to the heart.

93
00:03:58.004 --> 00:03:59.677
Then medial and lateral.

94
00:03:59.677 --> 00:04:02.688
Medial means toward the midline of the body.

95
00:04:02.688 --> 00:04:05.197
Lateral means away from the midline.

96
00:04:05.197 --> 00:04:08.041
The thumb is lateral to the little finger.

97
00:04:08.041 --> 00:04:11.722
Proximal and distal apply specifically to the limbs.

98
00:04:11.722 --> 00:04:15.988
Proximal means closer to where the limb attaches to the trunk.

99
00:04:15.988 --> 00:04:19.417
Distal means farther from that attachment point.

100
00:04:19.417 --> 00:04:21.759
The elbow is proximal to the wrist,

101
00:04:21.759 --> 00:04:24.352
while the wrist is distal to the elbow.

102
00:04:24.352 --> 00:04:28.869
A quick way to remember: proximal suggests proximity to the trunk,

103
00:04:28.869 --> 00:04:31.462
and distal suggests distance from it.

104
00:04:31.462 --> 00:04:33.553
Finally, superficial and deep.

105
00:04:33.553 --> 00:04:36.732
Superficial means closer to the body surface.

106
00:04:36.732 --> 00:04:39.241
Deep means farther from the surface.

107
00:04:39.241 --> 00:04:41.667
Skin is superficial to the muscles,

108
00:04:41.667 --> 00:04:43.925
and bones are deep to the muscles.

109
00:04:43.925 --> 00:04:46.048
Now that you know the body's planes,

110
00:04:46.048 --> 00:04:48.095
you can describe how joints move.

111
00:04:48.095 --> 00:04:51.052
Each movement happens within a specific plane.

112
00:04:51.052 --> 00:04:54.388
Flexion means decreasing the angle between two body

113
00:04:54.388 --> 00:04:55.601
parts, like bending.

114
00:04:55.601 --> 00:04:59.392
Extension means increasing that angle, like straightening.

115
00:04:59.392 --> 00:05:01.439
Both occur in the sagittal plane.

116
00:05:01.439 --> 00:05:03.334
Bending your elbow is flexion.

117
00:05:03.334 --> 00:05:05.684
Straightening it again is extension.

118
00:05:05.684 --> 00:05:09.323
Abduction means moving a limb away from the body's midline.

119
00:05:09.323 --> 00:05:12.508
Adduction means moving it back toward the midline.

120
00:05:12.508 --> 00:05:14.100
Both occur in the coronal,

121
00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:15.161
or frontal, plane.

122
00:05:15.161 --> 00:05:18.725
A memory aid: abduction takes you absent from the midline,

123
00:05:18.725 --> 00:05:20.469
and adduction adds you back.

124
00:05:20.469 --> 00:05:23.122
Rotation means turning around a long axis.

125
00:05:23.122 --> 00:05:25.776
Medial rotation turns toward the midline;

126
00:05:25.776 --> 00:05:27.595
lateral rotation turns away.

127
00:05:27.595 --> 00:05:29.870
This occurs in the transverse plane.

128
00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:32.296
The forearm has two special movements.

129
00:05:32.296 --> 00:05:35.935
Pronation rotates the forearm so the palm faces downward.

130
00:05:35.935 --> 00:05:38.892
Supination rotates it so the palm faces upward.

131
00:05:38.892 --> 00:05:42.759
Think of supination as the position for holding a bowl of soup.

132
00:05:42.759 --> 00:05:44.275
The ankle adds four more.

133
00:05:44.275 --> 00:05:46.549
Dorsiflexion pulls the foot upward,

134
00:05:46.549 --> 00:05:47.535
toward the shin.

135
00:05:47.535 --> 00:05:49.809
Plantar flexion points it downward,

136
00:05:49.809 --> 00:05:52.008
like a ballet dancer pointing toes.

137
00:05:52.008 --> 00:05:54.055
Inversion turns the sole inward,

138
00:05:54.055 --> 00:05:55.268
toward the midline.

139
00:05:55.268 --> 00:05:57.694
Eversion turns it outward, away from it.

140
00:05:57.694 --> 00:06:02.319
Finally, circumduction combines all four movements in sequence: flexion,

141
00:06:02.319 --> 00:06:04.594
extension, abduction, and adduction.

142
00:06:04.594 --> 00:06:07.854
Together they produce a cone-shaped range of motion,

143
00:06:07.854 --> 00:06:09.825
best seen at the shoulder joint.

144
00:06:09.825 --> 00:06:14.744
Bone is remarkable because it is both hard and flexible at the same time.

145
00:06:14.744 --> 00:06:18.746
That balance comes from two components working together.

146
00:06:18.746 --> 00:06:21.164
The first is the organic component,

147
00:06:21.164 --> 00:06:24.999
making up about thirty-five percent of bone's dry weight.

148
00:06:24.999 --> 00:06:31.336
This is primarily collagen, a protein that gives bone its flexibility and tensile strength.

149
00:06:31.336 --> 00:06:33.920
Collagen is produced by osteoblasts,

150
00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:35.504
the bone-forming cells.

151
00:06:35.504 --> 00:06:38.756
Without collagen, bone would shatter on impact,

152
00:06:38.756 --> 00:06:40.007
the way glass does.

153
00:06:40.007 --> 00:06:42.425
The second component is inorganic,

154
00:06:42.425 --> 00:06:45.426
making up the remaining sixty-five percent.

155
00:06:45.426 --> 00:06:50.762
This is primarily hydroxyapatite, a crystalline calcium-phosphate mineral.

156
00:06:50.762 --> 00:06:55.097
Hydroxyapatite provides hardness and compressive strength.

157
00:06:55.097 --> 00:06:57.765
Without it, bone would bend like rubber.

158
00:06:57.765 --> 00:07:00.350
Think of it like reinforced concrete.

159
00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:02.601
Collagen plays the role of steel

160
00:07:02.601 --> 00:07:04.686
rebar, providing flexibility.

161
00:07:04.686 --> 00:07:09.355
Hydroxyapatite plays the role of the concrete, providing hardness.

162
00:07:09.355 --> 00:07:10.772
Neither works alone.

163
00:07:10.772 --> 00:07:15.358
Together, they create a material that is both strong and resilient.

164
00:07:15.358 --> 00:07:17.359
This matters beyond anatomy.

165
00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:22.028
If you are studying calcium homeostasis in biochemistry this week,

166
00:07:22.028 --> 00:07:28.031
the same calcium ions that build hydroxyapatite in bone are regulated by parathyroid

167
00:07:28.031 --> 00:07:29.698
hormone and calcitonin.

168
00:07:29.698 --> 00:07:32.116
When you encounter those pathways,

169
00:07:32.116 --> 00:07:33.700
connect them back here.

170
00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:38.699
Inside the hollow spaces of bone lives a specialised tissue called bone marrow.

171
00:07:38.699 --> 00:07:40.516
There are two distinct types,

172
00:07:40.516 --> 00:07:42.561
and each has a very different job.

173
00:07:42.561 --> 00:07:45.818
Red bone marrow is found within the spaces of spongy,

174
00:07:45.818 --> 00:07:47.030
or cancellous, bone.

175
00:07:47.030 --> 00:07:51.271
In adults, it sits mainly in flat bones like the sternum and the ilium,

176
00:07:51.271 --> 00:07:53.543
and in the rounded ends of long bones.

177
00:07:53.543 --> 00:07:56.194
This is where haematopoiesis takes place.

178
00:07:56.194 --> 00:07:59.526
Haematopoiesis is the production of all blood cells,

179
00:07:59.526 --> 00:08:02.480
including red cells, white cells, and platelets.

180
00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:05.888
Clinically, this matters because a bone marrow biopsy,

181
00:08:05.888 --> 00:08:08.236
taken from the posterior iliac crest,

182
00:08:08.236 --> 00:08:10.887
is the standard way to diagnose leukaemia,

183
00:08:10.887 --> 00:08:13.083
anaemia, and other blood disorders.

184
00:08:13.083 --> 00:08:16.264
Yellow bone marrow occupies the medullary cavity,

185
00:08:16.264 --> 00:08:19.900
the hollow shaft running through the centre of long bones.

186
00:08:19.900 --> 00:08:22.021
It consists mainly of adipocytes,

187
00:08:22.021 --> 00:08:25.959
which are fat cells, and functions as a reserve of stored energy.

188
00:08:25.959 --> 00:08:29.594
What makes yellow marrow remarkable is its adaptability.

189
00:08:29.594 --> 00:08:31.563
In severe blood loss or anaemia,

190
00:08:31.563 --> 00:08:37.244
yellow marrow can convert back into red marrow and resume producing blood cells on demand.

191
00:08:37.244 --> 00:08:40.500
Think of the medullary cavity as a fuel storage tank,

192
00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:45.120
and the spongy regions as the production floor where blood cells are made.

193
00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:48.453
To remember this: red marrow produces red blood cells,

194
00:08:48.453 --> 00:08:50.725
and yellow marrow stores yellow fat.

195
00:08:50.725 --> 00:08:52.676
A radiologist sends a report.

196
00:08:52.676 --> 00:08:56.740
It describes a tumour in the medial aspect of the right thigh,

197
00:08:56.740 --> 00:08:58.121
proximal to the knee.

198
00:08:58.121 --> 00:09:00.072
Where exactly is this tumour?

199
00:09:00.072 --> 00:09:03.242
Option A says it is on the outer side of the thigh,

200
00:09:03.242 --> 00:09:04.136
near the knee.

201
00:09:04.136 --> 00:09:07.306
Option B says it is on the inner side of the thigh,

202
00:09:07.306 --> 00:09:08.119
near the hip.

203
00:09:08.119 --> 00:09:11.289
Option C says it is on the inner side of the thigh,

204
00:09:11.289 --> 00:09:12.183
near the knee.

205
00:09:12.183 --> 00:09:15.597
And Option D says it is on the outer side of the thigh,

206
00:09:15.597 --> 00:09:16.409
near the hip.

207
00:09:16.409 --> 00:09:18.197
Work through the two terms.

208
00:09:18.197 --> 00:09:21.124
Medial means toward the midline of the body.

209
00:09:21.124 --> 00:09:24.619
That places the tumour on the inner side of the thigh.

210
00:09:24.619 --> 00:09:29.333
Proximal means closer to the root of the limb than the reference point.

211
00:09:29.333 --> 00:09:31.934
Proximal to the knee means in the thigh,

212
00:09:31.934 --> 00:09:33.072
close to the knee.

213
00:09:33.072 --> 00:09:34.616
The correct answer is C.

214
00:09:34.616 --> 00:09:37.461
The tumour is on the inner side of the thigh,

215
00:09:37.461 --> 00:09:38.355
near the knee.

216
00:09:38.355 --> 00:09:42.500
Medial gives the side, and proximal to the knee gives the level.

217
00:09:42.500 --> 00:09:46.472
Here is a question to check your understanding of anatomical planes.

218
00:09:46.472 --> 00:09:50.792
A computed tomography scan of the abdomen is taken in the transverse plane.

219
00:09:50.792 --> 00:09:54.276
Each scan produces a series of image slices through the body.

220
00:09:54.276 --> 00:09:57.132
Based on what you know about the transverse plane,

221
00:09:57.132 --> 00:09:59.153
consider this question carefully.

222
00:09:59.153 --> 00:10:03.195
Which of the following best describes how each slice divides the body?

223
00:10:03.195 --> 00:10:06.051
Does it divide the body into right and left halves?

224
00:10:06.051 --> 00:10:08.908
Does it divide the body into front and back halves?

225
00:10:08.908 --> 00:10:11.835
Does it divide the body into upper and lower halves?

226
00:10:11.835 --> 00:10:15.597
Or does each slice represent a diagonal section through the body?

227
00:10:15.597 --> 00:10:17.339
Take a moment before moving on.

228
00:10:17.339 --> 00:10:21.102
Think about what you know about the three main anatomical planes.

229
00:10:21.102 --> 00:10:23.401
The transverse plane, the coronal plane,

230
00:10:23.401 --> 00:10:27.303
and the sagittal plane each divide the body in a distinct direction.

231
00:10:27.303 --> 00:10:28.767
When you have your answer,

232
00:10:28.767 --> 00:10:31.275
move to the next slide to find out how you did.

233
00:10:31.275 --> 00:10:35.906
Here is a scenario to test what you have learned about bone composition.

234
00:10:35.906 --> 00:10:39.124
A child presents with bones that fracture easily,

235
00:10:39.124 --> 00:10:42.420
even though calcium levels are completely normal.

236
00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:46.580
Investigations reveal that the child has vitamin C deficiency,

237
00:10:46.580 --> 00:10:48.542
the condition known as scurvy.

238
00:10:48.542 --> 00:10:53.408
The question is: which component of bone is primarily affected in this case?

239
00:10:53.408 --> 00:10:55.763
The first option is hydroxyapatite,

240
00:10:55.763 --> 00:11:00.472
the mineral salt that gives bone its hardness and compressive strength.

241
00:11:00.472 --> 00:11:02.434
The second option is collagen,

242
00:11:02.434 --> 00:11:06.908
the organic matrix that provides flexibility and tensile strength.

243
00:11:06.908 --> 00:11:09.420
The third option is yellow bone marrow,

244
00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:11.853
found within the shafts of long bones.

245
00:11:11.853 --> 00:11:15.228
And the fourth option is haematopoietic stem cells,

246
00:11:15.228 --> 00:11:18.367
which produce blood cells within the red marrow.

247
00:11:18.367 --> 00:11:22.370
Pause here, think about the role of vitamin C in bone structure,

248
00:11:22.370 --> 00:11:24.175
and then select your answer.

249
00:11:24.175 --> 00:11:26.556
Here is a question to test your recall.

250
00:11:26.556 --> 00:11:29.935
A patient is diagnosed with severe aplastic anaemia.

251
00:11:29.935 --> 00:11:33.160
Which marrow conversion would you expect to occur?

252
00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:37.691
Option A states that red marrow converts to yellow marrow in flat bones.

253
00:11:37.691 --> 00:11:40.917
In aplastic anaemia, the body needs more blood cell

254
00:11:40.917 --> 00:11:42.222
production, not less.

255
00:11:42.222 --> 00:11:46.062
This conversion would move in the wrong direction entirely.

256
00:11:46.062 --> 00:11:51.131
Option B states that yellow marrow converts back to red marrow in the long bones.

257
00:11:51.131 --> 00:11:52.283
Hold that thought.

258
00:11:52.283 --> 00:11:55.662
Option C says haematopoiesis moves to the liver only.

259
00:11:55.662 --> 00:12:00.961
Extramedullary haematopoiesis can occur, but it is not confined to the liver alone,

260
00:12:00.961 --> 00:12:04.417
and this option does not describe a marrow conversion.

261
00:12:04.417 --> 00:12:08.410
Option D suggests the medullary cavity fills with spongy bone.

262
00:12:08.410 --> 00:12:11.405
That is not a response seen in aplastic anaemia.

263
00:12:11.405 --> 00:12:12.864
The correct answer is B.

264
00:12:12.864 --> 00:12:17.088
In aplastic anaemia, the body faces severe haematopoietic stress.

265
00:12:17.088 --> 00:12:20.774
Yellow marrow, which is normally inactive adipose tissue,

266
00:12:20.774 --> 00:12:22.694
converts back into red marrow.

267
00:12:22.694 --> 00:12:25.536
This process is called marrow reconversion.

268
00:12:25.536 --> 00:12:31.142
It recruits the long bones back into active blood cell production when the body's demand

269
00:12:31.142 --> 00:12:33.292
exceeds the normal marrow output.

270
00:12:33.292 --> 00:12:36.825
This is a key compensatory response worth remembering.

271
00:12:36.825 --> 00:12:40.016
Key takeaways: Anatomical position: body upright,

272
00:12:40.016 --> 00:12:45.932
palms forward — the universal reference point for all anatomical descriptions Three body

273
00:12:45.932 --> 00:12:49.512
planes: Sagittal (right/left), Coronal/Frontal (front/back),

274
00:12:49.512 --> 00:12:54.183
Transverse (up/down) — remember SCT Directional pairs: Superior/Inferior,

275
00:12:54.183 --> 00:12:58.775
Anterior/Posterior, Medial/Lateral, Proximal/Distal, Superficial/Deep
